One last comment. To maybe close out on something positive. The *WHY*

When I master I’m looking to increase connection and help things to find their true form. It’s abstract but also kind of simple all at once

@Eric Martin just showed up and I did a master for him the other day. The mix was great, honestly hard to improve on. But using RX I was able to reduce a particular type of vocal resonance, once that was tended to I was able to EQ for maybe 5% more emotional connection

@Zakhiggins https://youtu.be/brXOrmgPCfE

These loudness videos are helpful for understanding the concept. But also, I don’t take my cue on how loud to make my mixes from any YouTuber/podcaster/plugin company/streaming platform. Cue into what your reference mixes sound like in tidal on hifi with normalization off. Route that into your DAW with a virtual output and you can compare LUFS on your favorite meters. The truth is there are no standards and trying to beat/cheat every loudness algorithm is folly. Make good shit that sounds like your favorite un-normalized records. 

Something else I have done, grab some CDs from a local library of your favorite records and put those wavs into a meter or RX and see what the pros are actually printing out loudness and peak wise.

@Gazing Wrmth | Mixes & Masters I’m pretty much exclusively in cans and i second all of what Noah said. Additionally, sonarworks for your headphones is definitely worth it esp. for only 70 USD. It will smear transients a bit, but you can get over that if you reference well. Mix quiet and you won’t be disappointed. 

Forgot to mention, because DT 770s are closed back, making sure you have a good seal and taking breaks are critical. You need a 15 minute break for every hour you put in on cans, bare minimum IMO. Without that, attention loss and fatigue kick in. 

Tools like tonal balance control 2 are important. I recommend setting up a Pro-MB with 3-5 bands across the entire frequency range but make them all neutral with no compression. Sub, low, mid, high mid, top end. You can monitor specific ranges now. And for sub/low end, you can turn the gain up on your headphone mix a bit, isolate the low end, and you can hear it a bit better. Make sure you turn your headphones down a bit before you un-solo the low or the sub, but this has helped me massively

Really helpful, thanks all @Calvin Lauber @sethearnest @Will Melones .

@willmix.studio#0 My experience with this kind of work is minimal! The thinking behind separate channels per song would be say if the drum mix wanted to be significantly different on each track, and then also just having complete freedom to go nuts on a sound without having to do everything as automation (or forget to, then wonder why the balance on track 1 is suddenly fucked).

But like you’re saying @Calvin Lauber , I think that level of detail might be impractical given the sheer amount of work to get through, and also unnecessary since as you say, it’s pretty much just one drum sound for the whole set. Maybe I could dup a channel here and there if I really wanted to go nuts on one song.

Ok to summarize- @cian riordan, our resident Grammy winning mixer, says
Dynamic EQ doesn’t need to be as ubiquitous as we think it does, but it’s useful for taming wild shit instead of clip fx or other more labor intensive solutions. 
@Nomograph Mastering, the discord godfather, says NEVER in a mastering context.

@Juliette Ok having heard the track, there’s a solo synth bass in there which is well designed sonically, when that drops out and the bass guitar comes back in, everything from about 60-70 cycles and below disappears except for the kick. So yeah I’d first try pumping low end into it, be it with EQ or subharmonic, followed by some (a lot) of compression. I’m sure better people here have a better way to do this. 

The DI itself doesn’t have any overtones other than stuff you’re finding unflattering, so you could try mult’ing the DI signal out to an amp sim (even some guitar amps work here) to fill out the spectrum that the guitars aren’t fulfilling 

I’d also say the bass drum could use some augmenting of the low end  and maybe a bit of length in order to emphasise that impact. Because the synth bass atm has all the power, and isn’t omnipresent, so it’s leaving the rest of the arrangement even _more_ neutered as a result

Thanks so much for all the replies everyone, really appreciate it, lots of good stuff here 🙏

@aliberger @Rob Domos totally feel you on the pitch-envelope side of things, that part actually makes a lot of sense to me.

@chrissoremI hear you about not overthinking and keeping it fun, I’m definitely guilty of going too deep sometimes lol.

What I’m mainly stuck on though is just getting clear transients when a few drums are going at once. Low end is fine (everything non-kick is high-passed), but the top end is where my kick transient sometimes gets masked by loops/percs. That’s why I mentioned the tiny time-offset thing, not big shifts, just few ms to see if it helps the transient poke through without messing up the groove @thegreatcarsoni. Not sure if that’s considered bad practice, but sometimes it feels like it helps.
